<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
  Project-local export options for `/deployit` macOS builds. deployit's
  ExportOptions ladder (bin/deployit-cli: DEPLOYIT_EXPORT_OPTIONS_PATH env ->
  .deployit/ExportOptions.<platform>.plist -> bundled default) picks this up
  automatically, overriding deployit's bundled `developer-id` default.

  Why `development` (not developer-id) — hard-won, see engineering-notes
  2026-06-23:
  The CloudKit environment follows the distribution channel, and a Developer-ID
  export is Production-ONLY (Apple rejects `iCloudContainerEnvironment =
  Development` for a developer-id profile). Production has no deployed schema
  (cutover deferred), so a Developer-ID macOS build can never sync with the
  Development-signed iOS build where the test data lives. Development-signing
  the macOS test build — exactly like iOS — puts it on the Development CloudKit
  database and lets it run on registered Macs (the target Mac's UDID must be in
  the team's Mac development profile; automatic signing + the
  `-allowProvisioningUpdates` deployit passes regenerate/fetch the latest
  profile incl. newly-registered devices).

  `iCloudContainerEnvironment` is intentionally OMITTED: the development profile
  implies Development (iOS does the same with no key). At the eventual shipping
  cutover, switch back to `developer-id` (Production) + notarization.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>method</key>
    <string>development</string>
    <key>signingStyle</key>
    <string>automatic</string>
</dict>
</plist>
